SPA219Y1-Y-20169.courseDescription: For native (heritage) speakers who have had exposure to spoken Spanish in an informal context (i.e, living in a Spanish-speaking country; or with a Spanish-speaking family), but little to no exposure to written Spanish. The students' ability to speak and understand Spanish may range from basic to relatively high fluency, but they cannot write and/or read Spanish. The course reviews English/Spanish spelling differences; written and spoken registers of Spanish, and basic aspects of the grammatical system. Provides students with the essential understanding of Spanish grammatical system; builds their vocabulary; and trains them to express themselves formally.
SPA219Y1-Y-20169.prerequisite: Basic to relatively high native ability to speak and understand Spanish; limited or no formal education in Spanish.
SPA219Y1-Y-20169.webTimetableInstructions: Students must enroll in the mandatory tutorial section on ACORN.

SPA220Y1-Y-20169.courseDescription: Intermediate Spanish for non-native speakers. Intensive grammar review of the structures of Spanish integrated with an introduction to reading authentic Spanish material, with practice designed to build vocabulary and to improve oral and written expression.
SPA220Y1-Y-20169.webTimetableInstructions: Students must enroll in the tutorial section that matches their lecture section. Please refer to the "Status/Notes" column next to each lecture for the corresponding tutorials.

SPA221H1-S-20169.courseDescription: A practical introduction to articulatory phonetics, Spanish sound patterns, phonetics, phonology; the basic concepts of phonetic description and transcription; the study of Spanish vowel and consonant systems, stress and intonation.
SPA221H1-S-20169.exclusion: SPA219Y1; native speakers of Spanish; SPA321H1

SPA258H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Introduction to university literary studies in Spanish and information literacy. Representative selection of Spanish and Spanish American prose, poetry, and drama, with focus on critical terminology and methods of literary analysis. Required for a program degree.

SPA322H1-F-20169.courseDescription: The basic concepts and analytic tools of linguistics applied to the study of Spanish, with a focus on the Spanish phonological, morphological, and syntactic systems. Theoretical discussion and practical exercises in analytic techniques.

SPA324H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Spanish bilingualism from three different perspectives: linguistic, sociolinguistic, psycholinguistic. Analysis of typical language contact phenomena with materials from Spanish. Case studies of Spanish in contact and discussion of the psychological consequences of bilingualism. Introduction to survey methods in sociolinguistics and psycholinguistics, and basic techniques for conducting language interviews. (Offered in alterante years)

SPA341H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Literary and artistic movements in Spain from 1890 to 1940, with special attention to the convergence and mutual mediation of politics and art. Materials to be studied include novels, poetry, the urban environment, graphic art, literary journals and manifestos, and some early Hispanic film. (Offered every three years)

SPA348H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Representative fiction by Galdós, the principal Spanish novelist of the nineteenth century. Detailed study of such texts as Marianela, Doña Perfecta, La desheredada, Realidad, La incognita, in relation to modernity of realist fiction and contemporary issues in politics, social relations and individual psychology. (Offered every three years)

SPA352H1-F-20169.courseTitle: Court and Country in Early Modern Spain
SPA352H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Representative texts (such as ballads, popular and courtly lyric; chivalric, pastoral and picaresque prose, theatre) from the early modern period, studied in relation to the history and society of imperial Spain. Discussion of literary texts as codes of social conduct; issues of urbanization, court culture, social order and disorder, and cultural discourses of identity and difference. (Offered every three years)

SPA375H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Latin American cinema approached within the framework of cultural studies and film theory, with attention to aesthetic and social forms, and to questions of national and cultural issues. May be focused on a particular region or period, or may be more of a representative survey, depending on instructor. (Offered in alternate years). Course taught in English.

SPA384H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Study of representative works of major artistic and literary movements in 20th and 21st century Spanish America: avant-garde poetry, theatre of the absurd, surrealist art, neo-realism, postmodernism. (Offered every three years)

SPA389H1-F-20169.courseTitle: Central American Literature: Narratives of War
SPA389H1-F-20169.courseDescription: The 70s and 80s represent a period of armed struggle, civil war, and revolution in most of Central America. Through the study of specific novels, short stories, and films, this course analyzes the representation of violence, and the political repression generated by military conflicts. (Offered every three years)

SPA420H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Linguistic analysis with the objective of improving students' command of Spanish grammar. Advanced review of traditional grammatical topics, including the verbal and pronominal systems, and Spanish copulas and embedded clauses. This course assumes familiarity with the grammatical terminology introduced in SPA220Y1.

SPA420H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Linguistic analysis with the objective of improving students' command of Spanish grammar. Advanced review of traditional grammatical topics, including the verbal and pronominal systems, and Spanish copulas and embedded clauses. This course assumes familiarity with the grammatical terminology introduced in SPA220Y1.

SPA421H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Study of Spanish morphology and syntax: syntactic categories in Spanish, the structure and interpretation of simple and complex sentences. (Offered in alternate years)

SPA422H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Study of linguistic variation across the Spanish-speaking world; central issues in phonological, morphological, and syntactic variation, analyzed from a geographical as well as from a social point of view. (Offered in alternate years)
SPA422H1-F-20169.prerequisite: SPA322H1 or permission of the department

SPA454H1-S-20169.courseDescription: Detailed study of Don Quixote as a foundational text in the European literary tradition, with attention to the conventions, genres, and literary techniques that inform the text.
SPA454H1-S-20169.prerequisite: At least one 300-series half-course in Spanish.

SPA467H1-S-20169.courseTitle: Topics in Spanish-American Literature and Culture
SPA467H1-S-20169.courseDescription: A course on a specific topic in Spanish American culture, designed for advanced students. Course content and instructor are established on a yearly basis.
SPA467H1-S-20169.prerequisite: At least one 300-series half-course in Spanish.

SPA480H1-F-20169.courseTitle: Icons and Iconography in Latin American Culture
SPA480H1-F-20169.courseDescription: Production, circulation and meaning of icons through Latin American literary and cultural contexts. Readings are selected from the period of independence to the present, and focus on the transformative ideological charge of cultural objects across geographic space and history. Focuses on political and socio-economic tensions between popular and elite spheres of cultural production, and on the risks and limits of iconographic representation. (Offered every three years)
SPA480H1-F-20169.prerequisite: At least one 300-series half-course in Spanish.
